Preface

Following vairables in file encounters.csv are relevant to average patient volume calculation:

  • PAT_ENC_CSN_ID: unique patient id
  • ADT_ARRIVAL_DTTM: the timestamp that a patient came into the ED
  • ACUITY_LEVEL_C: the acuities levels of a patient
  • BEHAVIORAL_DAHSB: whether the patient is a behavioral patient or not

Besides, we will create several new vairables for use:

  • ADT_YEAR, ADT_MONTH, ADT_WEEKDAYS, and ADT_HOUR

Data Inspection

Inspect the distribution of acuity


     1      2      3      4      5   null 
 11417  56315 130956 165372  31889   1372

As we can see, there are only 1372 observations with missing acuity level, which is a small percent and is relatively negligible. We decided to focus on the majority, and filter out those observations with missing acuity level in the data exploration process.

Overall Distribution of Patient Volume

  • Demand trend:

    • Down: Feburary

    • Up: July/August

    • Slightly Down: November

    • Surge: December

  • We see more variation in daily patient volumes in January, Feburary and December.

  • June, July and August have relatively low daily patient volume.

  • Peak appeared in January and Feburary.

Clearly, the average daily patient volumes across the whole week varied. But from the patient volume history that we have, we can only conclude that the patient volume on Tuesday is normally different from that of Friday and Saturday (95% confidence). The plot showed that Monday and Tuesday tend to have more patients, but there’s not a statistically significant difference compare to other days of the week.

Currently, ED use Tuesday through Saturday, as well as Monday and Sunday as the way of grouping weekdays. We think this may require reconsidering and further analysis.

The differences of average patient volume across different months are greater. After Bonferroni adjustment (which reduce the likelihood of incorrectly reject the null hypothesis), we can roughly group them into three clusters:

  • January, Feburary, March, and December
  • April, May, September, October, and November
  • June, July, August

Linear Regression Model

To quantify the difference, we run a simple linear regression, using just Year, Month and Weekdays to explain the average patient volumes. Due to the fact that year 2018 only has the first 4 month data, so we exclude all observations recorded in year 2018.

The Base case is the average patient volume of all Mondays in January, 2014. We saw a year-on-year growth. We also observe that February is probably on average the busiest month, whereas July is the month that on average has the least amount of patients. One thing that is counter-intuitive is that Tuesday being the busiest day through the week averagely.

Average Patient Volume By Acuities

The graph showed that the distribution of different acuities shares the same pattern across the weekdays.
